Civil Rights Movement Issues Travel Alert for Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) has issued a warning to colored people traveling to Missouri based on discriminatory state policies and racist attacks.
“NAACP’s travel recommendation for the state of Missouri, effective August 28, 2017, calls on African-American travelers, visitors, and residents of Missouri to pay more attention when traveling across the state as a result of a series of controversial racially motivated incidents currently taking place across the state,” the association said in a statement.
The NAACP said it took this step on the basis of current Missouri law, which makes it difficult to defend racist acts in court, as well as the actions of law enforcement agencies that disproportionately target minorities.
“Civil rights are being violated.
People are stopped by police officers just because of the color of their skin, they are attacked or killed,” Rod Chapel, president of the NAACP, told the Kansas City Star.
"We have the largest number of complaints to date."
This is the first warning of its kind issued by the organization for the state of the United States.
Among the incidents cited by the organization were racially motivated insults directed at black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died in controversial circumstances earlier this year after he ran out of gas while traveling across the country and was thrown into custody by police without being charged with a crime.
The travel recommendation also draws attention to a recent statement by the Missouri Attorney General’s Office, which states that black drivers are 75 percent more likely to be stopped by police.
“The purpose of the travel recommendation is to alert people and warn their families, friends and co-workers about what might happen in Missouri,” Chapel said.
"People need to be prepared - they should carry money with them to pay bail or alert their relatives that they are going to travel to the state."
According to the current FBI program, there were 100 cases of hateful behavior in Missouri in 2015, which puts the state 16th among all states.
The travel alert is also a response to a new Missouri law that makes it harder for companies to sue for discrimination in the provision of accommodation or employment.
The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) issued travel recommendations for Texas and Arizona after states passed an immigration law that allows state officials to detain people for violating the law, which the ACLU says is meant to improve racial profiling.
Travel recommendations are usually issued by the State Department for foreign countries, but more recently, advocacy groups have resorted to these measures in response to specific laws and trends within the US.
