Poverty and Death in Indonesia’s Gold Country
When Bardina Degei cooks dinner, she doesn't use the stove.
In fact, it rarely uses a frying pan.
In her wooden hut, located in the capital Paniai Enarotali in the Indonesian province of Papua, a woman usually simply throws a sweet potato - in the local language "note" - directly into the fire.
After half an hour, remove the potatoes and taste them with unwashed hands.
Bardina sits on muddy ground - the house is not equipped with furniture - where she also performs her daily work, such as washing laundry in cloudy water from a nearby swamp.
A bucket in a room without a roof complements the toilet.
As the youngest of the four wives of her husband, she was not assigned any field to cultivate.
Polygamy is common here.
Work until late at night poses a danger: most of the men in the village are unemployed and often drink alcohol.
"In the afternoon, after five o'clock, no one will allow themselves to wander around the village," Bardina says.
It is a rare glimpse into everyday life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was declared part of Indonesia in 1969 after a controversial referendum, when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote in the form of a public handshake before the occupying army.
The current movement protesting against Dutch rules quickly turned its anger against the Jakarta government, which controlled the entire region with the exception of foreign journalists or civil rights watchdogs.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua - independent Papua New Guinea occupied the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is such a remote and devastated city that you can get there after a 90-minute flight from the capital of Jayapura province to Nabire, and then a five-hour stomach jamming ride.
Public transport in this place does not work.
The city of 19,000 inhabitants consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, roofs of woolen sheets in shades of gray and rusty color.
Very few Indonesians looked at this place, let alone journalists, and practically no foreigners.
Before the arrival of the Christians, the locals worshipped a god named Uga Tamee.
And that's not all.
“We weren’t used to wearing these dresses,” Bardina says, pointing to her colorful, hand-knitted turban, dark t-shirt, and bright skirt.
"We used to wear only leaves."
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, with 28% of the population living below the poverty line, and the country’s child mortality and literacy rate is one of the worst in all of Asia.
At the same time, it is the Indonesian country of gold.
The world’s largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Freeport McMoran of Phoeenix, is located just 60 miles from Paniai – a rocky province roughly the size of New Jersey that is home to about 153,000 residents.
In 2015, Freeport mined $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua supports the extraction of wood at an estimated value of $78 billion.
However, these riches are a source of suffering for the Papuans and a guarantee of oppression by the powerful Indonesian army.
According to a 2005 New York Times investigation, Freeport paid local military officials and units about $20 million between 1998 and 2004, including $150,000 for one officer.
Papuans calling for self-government threaten this golden goose and are therefore severely suppressed.
According to human rights activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed since 1969 and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian military.
The mass murders in the tribal region of Papua during the 1970s amounted to genocide, according to the Asian Commission on Human Rights.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
We Will Lose Everything, a 2016 report by the Archdiocese of Brisbane, describes the atrocities that took place last year as extrajudicial executions, torture – according to another report, particularly popular rape and electrocution – and brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrators.
“It’s hard to count the number of victims because incidents happen every week,” said Andreas Harsono, an Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch.
The situation was aggravated by the fact that Papuan sources attract colonists to Indonesia.
Of the 3.5 million inhabitants of the province, 83% are Christian, but the demographics change with the influx of Muslim immigrants from the Indonesian islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javan canteens sell fried chicken and gado-gado, or a mixture of vegetables with peanut sauce.
Local people are fighting for survival.
“Immigrants have started selling chickens and vegetables in traditional markets at lower prices than local Papuans,” explains Abeth You, a 24-year-old who was born in Paniai and moved to the capital Jayapura to work.
"The original inhabitants of Papua - mother-mother (women) - lost their jobs."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, nicknamed Jokowi, pledged to address inequality and rights abuses as part of his 2014 presidential campaign.
The former carpenter also secured his way to the presidential palace in Jakarta in 27 of the 29 districts of Papua, including Paniai.
But very little has changed in Papua, and the local people feel betrayed.
“Our hearts were broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokpwi in the hope that he would hear our call for justice,” he said.
The fact is that just two months after Jakowi’s inauguration in October, Paniai experienced a major shock.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children sang a Christmas song at a camp fire in Enarotali, Indonesia, as two Indonesian soldiers emerged from the twilight of the night.
Two of the surprised children told them to turn on the lights.
One of the soldiers was touched by this reproach and the tone with which it was uttered, and later returned with four other soldiers, said local parish priest Yavedt Tebai.
Two of the soldiers, in a drunken state, chased a group of children and beat them with the arms of their arms, the victims and witnesses of the event said.
One of the soldiers then fired at a group of children.
One of the children, 16-year-old Julianus Yeimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, someone set fire to a nearby election commission building, and the next day things got worse.
About 1,000 young Papuan men and women gathered on a football field outside the local police station and army headquarters to demand justice.
They came with ceremonial hunting bows and performed the Waita dance - which runs in a circle and imitates the singing of birds - the Papuan tribe of Mee Pago.
Several Protestants began throwing stones at the buildings.
With increasing tension, the soldiers were ordered via radio: “If the crowd tries to resist at least three times, you are allowed to shoot,” the official document, which was never published in local media, said.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, the head of the Enarotali district of Kego Koto, recognized the impending danger and urged residents to disperse to their homes.
But no one cared about his words.
"When I turned around, someone shot me in the left wrist," he told TIME on the porch of his colorfully painted wooden house.
Kayame did not know who the shooter was, but he said the bullet belonged to one of the soldiers present.
"There were a lot of people around and a lot of shooting," he added.
One of the locals, Alfius Youw, said his cousin, who witnessed the shooting, had been hit three times.
“I ran to the body to make sure it was really him,” Yohanes, who, like many Indonesians, uses only one name, told TIME in a sad voice.
"I saw that he was dead... I kissed him."
The Papuan police inspector, General Yotje Mende, told reporters that his officers were only “securing” the station that was under attack.
“We have to defend ourselves when people threaten us with death,” said a spokesman for the Papuan police, Commissioner Pudjo Sulistiyo, in 2015.
"It's a matter of life and death."
According to Human Rights Watch, five protesters were killed and many escaped injuries.
The report of the murders was leaked by the Jakarta media the following day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi delivered a passionate speech in Jayapura, expressing his understanding for the families of the victims and promising to address the violence in Papua.
"I demand an immediate solution to this problem so that it can never happen again," he said.
National Security Minister Wiranto announced in October 2016 that he would introduce an extrajudicial mechanism to resolve acts of violence that have occurred in the past.
Almost immediately, however, excuses began to be heard.
“Most of the violence happened a long time ago.
Some of them took place in the 1990s and some in the early 21st century.
I mean, we are determined to punish these acts of violence, but it will not be an easy task," he said.
However, in an interview on June 5 for the TIME weekly held in Jakarta, Wiranto claimed that he did not plan to introduce any measures in Papua.
Instead, he said, “all cases will be brought to trial.”
Wiranto, who was accused by the UN of “crimes against humanity” on the basis of more than 1,000 deaths during the 1999 independent elections in East Timor, said 11 human rights cases had been settled so far in Papua, including the Paniai incident.
The families of the victims of the Paniai shooting welcomed his claims with distrust.
“I’ve been interviewed four times in the last three years, but I haven’t seen anything yet,” Yohanes said.
"I'm tired."
A few years later, he still lives in fear.
"I'm scared," he says.
"I'm afraid the army will arrest me or someone will shoot me."
His brother Yacobus confirmed the view of many residents of Paniai who are afraid to speak about the incident.
According to him, he was beaten by members of the army after helping to bury four of the victims.
"After the bodies were buried, the army started looking for me," he said.
And the shooting hasn't stopped yet.
Indonesian police fired on villagers in neighboring Deiyai on Tuesday.
The clash, in which one person died and another 17 were injured, occurred between villagers and the manager of a construction company, who refused to provide assistance in transporting the man unconscious to the hospital.
Ravianus Douw, 24, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on his way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the company building.
According to the police, the villagers threw stones at the members, and the answer was a warning shot.
