“I didn’t leave the house for two days.”
The Deiyai parliament demanded the punishment of the involved police officers and the withdrawal of the mobile brigade from the area.
Paniai has always been a thorn in the eye for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development only deepens the separation of the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribes, who live in the central highlands.
Many have joined the Papua Liberation Movement (OPM), a rebel army that protects the rights of Papuans by attacking and kidnapping Indonesian police officers.
Some of OPM's leaders come from Paniai, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
As a result of the attacks, the army has arrested and arbitrarily detained thousands of Paniai residents in recent years, all under the guise of “ensuring national sovereignty.”
Some of them will never be seen again.
Paniai is known among Papuans as a “tragic and forgotten place”.
Poverty pours oil into the fire.
The little rice sold in Enarotali is too expensive for the locals.
And bread is equally unattainable.
The locals grow their food: mainly sweet potatoes, fruits and leafy vegetables.
Women work in the fields; each of them cultivates four or five fields with sweet potatoes.
Most of the harvest is intended for the needs of the family, the rest is sold on the local market.
Ten pieces of sweet potatoes cost only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Since Nabire Airport opened more air routes and new immigrants began to flow into the country, there has been an increase in economic inequality between native Papuans and immigrants.
Fewer jobs are usually filled by more educated and wealthy immigrants.
Papuans rarely have the capital and education they need to start a business.
“Young people are moving out of villages because of a lack of jobs and money,” said John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai tribal council.
Thanks to isolation, the province of Papua is hidden from the world.
Strict rules for foreign journalists also contribute to this.
Earlier this year, two French journalists - Franck Escudie and Basile Longchamp - were expelled from the papaya for "lack of cooperation with the authorities", despite the fact that they received such a rare permission to film.
Phelim Kine, deputy director of the Asian branch of Human Rights Watch, promised in his election campaign to abolish strict rules for journalists and achieve transparency and development, but this never happened.
“Foreign journalists working in the rebellious easternmost regions of Papua and West Papua face a great risk: non-recognition of visas and blacklisting,” he said in a statement.
The lack of reports from foreign journalists means that international pressure on Indonesia in the case of Papua is largely limited.
In March, six Pacific nations - Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands - urged the UN Human Rights Council to investigate "various and widespread acts of violence" in Papua, including the Paniai shooting.
These countries have also supported OPM in the past.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arrmanatha Nasir shook off the charges when he told reporters in Jakarta that: “In Indonesia, the democratic system is still in place and the media is free, so it is difficult to disguise evidence of human rights violations.”
Local people are calling for the participation of foreign governments.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by human rights envoy Kees Van Baar, visited Jayapura on May 4, local people shouted, according to a source who also attended the meeting but wanted to remain anonymous, the slogan “we want freedom”.
In 2019, Indonesia is planning another election, but the Papuans say they will not vote for Jokowi.
"Jokowi is a man with good intentions but surrounded by people associated with the Paniai shooting," said Gobau, chairman of the tribal council.
He wants Jokowi to know that the inhabitants of Paniai - in addition to living in constant fear of a robbing army - are waving in poverty, poor education and a health system.
Gobai argues that the inhabitants of Paniai, like other Papuans, consider their voice to be a "debt" to be paid to Jok.
"They don't want money, they demand justice," he added.
Despite the threats and intimidation of the family of the victims of the Panai shooting, they continue the last symbolic act of defiance: they bury the bodies of the victims on the plot opposite the police and army station.
Knowing that justice will never be done enough, at least it will not allow those responsible to forget their crimes.
"A member of our family was killed," Yacobus said with his head down.
"What can we do?"
