EPA Chief Scott Pruitt on the postponement of the planned directives to reduce emissions of the Obama administration
After the Environmental Protection Agency was sued by 15 states, its chief, Scott Pruitt, revoked his earlier decision to postpone the implementation of the former Obama administration’s plan to reduce carbon dioxide emissions.
Pruitt introduced changes to his plan, responding more rapidly than previous governments to the needs of state environmental regulators.
However, he did not mention a legal challenge filed against his previous position at the federal appeals court.
This refers to the last deadline set for October 1st, when countries should begin to comply with the 2015 regulation to reduce the amount of ground-level ozone.
Pruitt announced in June that he would postpone the deal by one year and order a more detailed study of the plan to avoid “interference with local decisions or impending economic growth.”
Pruitt, who served as Oklahoma’s Attorney General prior to President Donald Trump’s appointment as EPA chief, has long served as a staunch opponent of stricter environmental regulations.
Since settling in Washington, Pruitt has repeatedly moved or delayed regulations proposed by the chemical and fossil industry.
Wednesday’s sudden turnaround is the biggest legal failure for Pruitt’s regulatory agenda.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the EPA executive exceeded its authority in an effort to delay the Obama administration’s plan to require oil and gas companies to reduce methane leaks.
In a statement issued on Wednesday evening, Pruitt proposed his version of ozone standards and strengthened the EPA’s commitment to working with states through complex processes and meeting new standards within a given timeframe.
“Under the previous administration, the EPA often failed to meet deadlines and waited for it to be sued by activist groups and others, agreeing to settle and further set up plans,” said Pruitt, who filed more than a dozen lawsuits at the EPA in his previous position.
“We don’t believe in regulation through litigation and we take compliance seriously.
We never joke about our status and the authority that comes from it.”
However, the EPA said in a statement that Pruitt may at some point use “the possibility of delay and all other legally available authorities” to ensure that regulations “will be based on sound policies and the most accessible information”.
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a more comprehensive rewrite of the ozone rules.
The White House budget approved last month seeks to delay implementation of the 2015 rules by at least eight years.
The measure was still not passed by the Senate.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who led the coalition of states that sued the EPA this week, said the group did not intend to allow legal coercion.
“The turnaround in the EPA’s views – following our litigation – is an important victory for the health and safety of those 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans directly affected by air pollution,” Schneiderman said.
New York was joined by California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont, Washington and Washington, D.C.
Ground-level ozone occurs when common harmful substances emitted by cars, power plants, oil refineries, chemical power plants and other sources react in the atmosphere with sunlight.
The resulting smog can cause severe respiratory problems in sensitive people and thousands of premature deaths each year.
Public health advocates and environmentalists are grateful for Pruitt’s sudden change.
“It’s worrying what kind of pressure needs to be put on to change the minds of responsible people and protect the air we breathe,” said Lori Ann Burd of the Center for Biological Diversity.
“We must continue to fight the ideological campaign of the Trump administration, which is trying to help polluters and special interests.”
