China lacks tourists.
Beijing is losing billions due to visa policy.
China has been trying for decades to exert its influence without the use of force.
He spends $10 billion annually to support language schools and build universities abroad, pushing his entertainment industry into foreign markets and trying to attract Western tourists.
Beijing is not succeeding.
The state media are talking about the plan to make tourism the driving force of economic change and modernization.
However, the number of arrivals last year increased by only 3.8 percent, and about 80 percent of tourists to China came from Hong Kong, Macau and Taiwan.
This is due, among other things, to the fact that despite all its global aspirations, China does not welcome foreigners with open arms, according to Christopher Balding, professor of economics at Beijing University, in an article for Bloomberg.
An example that speaks for itself is China’s visa policy.
Only 13 countries have visa-free travel with China, and citizens of the other countries have to deal with their visas in advance.
In the United States, Chinese New Year celebrations are similar to Chinese New Year celebrations.
A visa costs $140, but if you don’t want to wait long hours in line for it, you have to pay $100 or more for additional services.
Such restrictions create significant economic barriers.
A study by the Journal of Economics and Finance found that the need for a visa reduces the number of visitors by 70 percent.
In 2015, only two million Americans visited mainland China, while 1.8 million Americans visited Hong Kong, which accounts for less than three percent of China’s gross domestic product and is home to less than one percent of the total population.
China often deepens this problem by using tourism to pursue its political goals, for example in disputes with Taiwan and South Korea.
When China cut traffic to South Korea in the spring as part of a rift over South Korea’s anti-missile system, the South Koreans retaliated and shunned China.
In May, the number of visits fell by 42% year-on-year, while Japan saw an increase of 85%.
All of this affects macroeconomic stability.
According to a recent Fed report, China may have left as much as $190 billion as a result of Chinese foreign travel, while China will receive about $35 billion annually in the sale of the currency to incoming tourists.
According to official figures on the development of the balance of payments, China had a deficit of $217 billion in tourism last year, which is equal to 44 percent of the total Chinese surplus in trade in goods.
A small number of tourists, therefore, inflicts a very painful blow on a country that is anxiously hindering the outflow of capital.
However, the above-mentioned factors are only one manifestation of a more general restraint towards foreigners.
In many places in China, almost no one has heard of immigrants.
In 2013, there were less than a million foreigners in China.
There are more of them in the United States and some individual cities.
Even Japan, which is not at the crossroads of immigration, has doubled.
A number of scientific papers show that immigrants usually boost economic growth, entrepreneurship and innovation.
You won’t find them in China.
Solving these problems will be politically challenging, but the step that is being offered is to simplify the visa system.
Other Asian countries, particularly India and Vietnam, have been making great efforts to simplify and reduce the cost of issuing visas.
If China wants more foreign tourists and their hard currencies, it should be easier for them to get there.
