Where can Czechs vote?
In the autumn parliamentary elections, registered voters will be able to vote again on the composition of the House of Representatives from Burma, Senegal or Luxembourg.
In these and several other countries, the Czech Republic has opened its representative offices since the last parliamentary elections in 2013.
It comes from a decree that regulates the delivery of ballots abroad.
The Ministry of Foreign Affairs has prepared an update and is currently in the process of commenting.
Four years ago, 10,000 Czech citizens voted for MPs abroad.
“Since the last amendment of the decree in 2013, there have been some changes that need to be taken into account in these lists,” the ministry explains.
“In some countries, new representative offices have been created, some offices have been closed, or the level of representation has changed,” the report said.
The decree contains two annexes, the first of which lists the representative offices to which paper ballots are delivered.
This group of offices includes the representation of the Czech Republic in neighboring countries, i.e. Germany, Poland, Austria and Slovakia.
More than a hundred Czech authorities will receive a ballot in the press version.
It is their list that is changing by decree.
Four years ago, for example, Czechs could vote at the Czech embassy in Libya or Zimbabwe.
Both embassies are closed today.
The Czech Republic has also abolished its representation in Bamako, Malaysia, and Kyoto, Japan.
There will be no elections at the Consulate General in Donetsk.
The Czech Republic closed it in 2014 because of the war in eastern Ukraine.
