Moore's Ford Bridge Massacre: Activists Recall Racist Lynching
A 1948 Ford Mercury drove past the watching residents of Monroe, Georgia, and curled towards the Moore's Ford Bridge.
But before a car with four black passengers and a white driver could get to the bridge, a group of white men with guns was behind it.
The leader of the group - a middle-aged man in a striped suit - pulled out of the cigarette and looked at the windshield of the car.
Inside, the passengers trembled with fear.
'We want that n--and Roger! 'shouted the man.
"Bring it to me!"
The silence is interrupted by the roar of a young black man who is pulled from the passenger seat.
Fortunately, this scene is just a reconstruction of the events that took place on July 22.
But when one of the men throws a rope over Roger's neck, the audience sighs with excitement.
Since 2005, a group of activists have returned to the Moore's Ford Bridge regularly to reconstruct that fateful night in 1946, when two black couples - Roger and Dorothy Malcolm and George and Mae Murra Dorsey - were killed by members of the Kukluxklan.
No one has been tried for the murders yet.
“It’s a wonder that there hasn’t been one person arrested in all these years — even though we still see them in our community; even though we know their identity,” Tyrone Brooks, who helps reconstruct the event, said in a statement.
"It's a stain on our history and a burden on our souls."
Brooks is a 71-year-old former Georgia congressman and a lifelong civil rights activist.
In his eyes, the reconstruction of the event presents a dramatic challenge to take place, reminding the Monroe community each year that justice has not been done enough.
“We demand prosecution and closure of the case, we want peace of mind and reconciliation, but justice above all,” Brooks said.
“Until then, the process of healing and reconciliation cannot begin.”
On July 27, 1946, a medical examiner covered up one of the bodies of the lynching victims at Moore's Ford.
According to FBI files obtained by NBC News, up to 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties were expected to participate in the lynching.
No one has yet been prosecuted.
Despite the fact that the suspects remain at large for decades, civil rights advocates claim that both reasons for lynching – politics and sex – were known to all residents of the city.
In April 1946, by a decision of the Supreme Court, residents of the black state of Georgia were granted the right to participate for the first time in the elections scheduled for the summer.
And it was during the summer election that the FBI said Roger Malcolm, a black farmer, was supposed to stab Barnett Hester, the owner of the white-skinned land, during a skirmish, allegedly because of his wife.
According to Brooks, Hester was said to have associated with Malcolm's wife, Dorothy, and brought her to a different state.
On July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, then a major white-skinned landowner, filed a $600 bail on Malcolm.
He was accompanied to prison by Dorothy and his cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey.
On their return from prison, just before entering the Moore's Ford Bridge, a group of suspects blocked their way.
"As it turned out, the murders were planned and organized by Harrison," the FBI said.
“It is also clear that there was a secret agreement between state and local law enforcement, who not only participated in the lynching, but also got rid of the evidence and concealed the identity of the witnesses.”
Brooks made a brief statement on the matter.
"It was a massacre for the sake of the right to vote," he said.
“The murders had a clear undertone for all black locals: ‘This is how you’ll end up if you register and go vote.’”
The annual reenactment of the event at Moore’s Ford Bridge has been organized by Cassandra Greene for almost a decade.
Her performance is figurative, engaging and concise, showing a deep-seated racism that many would like to consider extinct in modern America.
Watching this reconstruction isn't easy, and it's even harder to distract, but Greene says it makes sense.
“No one wants to talk about lynching because we have to face the unpleasant feelings that are hidden in each of us,” Greene said.
"But there can be no relationship between us unless you listen to what I've been through."
The main rehearsals of this year's reconstruction began in June, and on the first day about 30 actors - a dozen whites, the rest blacks - gathered in the room, where Greene introduced them to a very carefully planned performance.
Wade Marbaugh is an assistant director.
For many years he played the leader of the Kukluxklan, but according to him, the role is exhausting.
"I feel bad because it's against who I am," Marbaugh said.
“I think it’s very important to remember this part of history on a regular basis, because we never want to go back to that time.”
Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, who play the role of Roger Malcolm, then Barnett Hester, rehearse their roles.
The show begins with a fight - Malcolm argues with Hester and accuses him of having slept with his wife.
"Get out of my land, n---e!"
Rascona can't be.
There's a fight going on.
At that moment, everyone (at least every actor of black skin) explodes in laughter.
Greene laughs the most.
"What happened?" asked Rascona.
He's confused.
Was I too rude?
'No, 'said Greene cheerfully.
"I just don't think the whites used to say 'n-r' in that tone."
"Exactly," said one of the black-skinned actors.
"You have to put more emphasis on R."
The energy in the room is suddenly better; hostility replaces the feeling of convergence.
Everyone wants the show to be authentic, just to be made for four victims of the massacre.
The actors repeat the scene.
This time Rascona emphasizes the correct pronunciation of the word on N.
No one's laughing now.
The show ends violently and quickly.
The roar, the gunshots... and the silence.
A woman dressed in black stands over the bodies of the actors and sings Billie Holiday's mournful song "Strange Fruit".
With every word, there is sadness in the room.
Against the backdrop of all this, about a dozen spectators wiped sweat and tears from their eyes.
There are almost the same number of blacks and whites in the audience.
One couple came all the way from Ithaca, New York, many of them from nearby.
Each of them endures the local humid climate for almost eight hours, and Brooks in the crowd leads them to the graves of Malcolm and Dorsey.
Up to this point, the murders could have been viewed with distance, but now, standing in the same place where the lynching took place, the atmosphere is horrifying.
With the last words of the song, Greene invites a crowd watching the bodies to be inspected.
The children kneel to the victims' heads, watch the fake blood and the immobile bodies and whisper something in their ear.
'They're not dead, 'said the little boy.
It'll be a few minutes, and Greene will thank the audience.
The actors clean the rope and wipe their tears.
Bradshaw embraces Marbaugh, the man in the suit who played the leader of the Kukluxklan.
Nick Rascona hugs his two fellow actors and cries in their arms; eventually he is overwhelmed with emotion.
"That's all right," one of the women whispered.
“We know you’re against the role.
But you had a reason for it.”
Later that day, the audience meets with the actors for dinner.
At one table, a young white couple is excited to talk about a show with a black couple they met today.
Denise Duplinski could scarcely find words to express her feelings about today's performance.
“It’s hard to listen to those ugly words and look at those disgusting things... people who look like you and do it because they look like you,” she said.
“It makes me realize that lynching is still a topical topic,” she added, “it’s just called a police fight.”
On the other side of the room, Tyrone Brooks sits in the courtroom, enjoying dinner and talking about civil rights.
According to his own words, he has already started planning the performance for the next year.
“Reconstruction of these events is inspiring because it describes the fear we had to experience – but it’s also a moment to think about,” he said.
"If we don't learn from it, who knows... it could happen again.
People who do not know and do not study the history of their country are doomed to repeat it.
