Latest results of tests to determine the age limit of asylum applications in Sweden
The latest results of tests of asylum seekers in Sweden, which were subjected to a new method of assessing their age, show that over 80 percent of people were interviewed as over 18 years of age, but not everyone believes their accuracy.
The Swedish Forensic Medical Agency (Rättsmedicinalverket) has started conducting new tests at the beginning of this year.
The aim of the method is to make a more accurate assessment of applicants in the evaluation of asylum applications. The measure was adopted after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticized for failing to determine the correct age of some refugees who lied about their age.
To date, the Swedish Migration Agency has submitted 6,880 cases to the investigation, and the Forensic Medical Agency has now published the results of a total of 2,481 tests conducted from mid-March to 31 July 2017.
80 percent (2002) were judged to be over 18 years of age, while in another 25 cases the Forensic Medical Agency judged the interviewee to be “possibly over 18 years of age”.
In another 423 cases, it was decided that the interviewee was “possibly under 18 years of age”.
Tests are only available if the age of the interviewee is disputed.
According to Johan G<0xC3><0x83><0xC2><0xB6>ransson of the Forensic Medical Agency, the results correspond to the previous month.
“Compared to last month, the statistics are kept in the running and the numbers are very similar,” he told The Local.
A higher number of applicants whose age has been estimated to be over 18 does not necessarily mean that asylum seekers lie about their age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests and said that in 442 cases it was found that "the subject is 18 years of age or older".
The Svenska Dagbladet newspaper investigated 581 published cases and found that in 243 cases the interviewee said he would be 18 this year.
The medical method of age determination, which includes wisdom teeth x-rays and MRI scans of the knee joints, which are subsequently assessed by dentists and x-ray scientists, was also criticized.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus of the Karolinska Institute, who, among other things, deals with assessing the biological maturity of people to determine the age at which the person went through puberty.
“I had reason to think about this issue and I don’t think these types of measurements to assess age are correct.
The assessment of biological age is, in a sense, very uncertain.
If we can't determine the age with precision, we shouldn't pretend otherwise," he told Metro.
Forensic medical agency Agency's G<0xC3><0x83><0xC2><0xB6>ransson defended the decision by saying: "In general, it can be said that the risk of misjudgment of a child as an adult is small.
The highest risk is the fact that the interviewee is just below the age of 18, which in this case corresponds to 10 percent of all respondents.
