Clubs can spend huge sums to buy players, but on the other hand, they have to prove legitimate sources of income, which allows them to cover the overhead of business activities related to football.
The FFP was introduced by Michel Platini after he was appointed UEFA Director in 2007.
The former French player believed that clubs in debt in pursuit of new reinforcements would ultimately cheat and risk bankruptcy if banks or owners refused to secure them.
In 2011, the FFP redirected its attention from club debts to monitoring their losses.
This change meant that the business model that Roman Abramovich used with Chelsea in 2003 – buying a club with potential and spending huge sums on players to build a global brand – suddenly wasn’t so profitable.
Under the current three-year trial period, which ends in 2018, clubs can report losses of up to EUR 30 million.
And despite Platini having to leave his post in 2015, his successor, Aleksander Ceferin, is determined to defend a ban on excessive spending.
“The FFP rules still apply and we are committed to strengthening them in the future,” Andrea Traverso, who oversees compliance with the FFP rules, told the Associated Press last week.
Although PSG has paid the amount of Neymar’s redemption as a lump sum, it may, for accounting purposes, spread the amount over the entire duration of the contract.
