The first wave of FFP sanctions hit PSG in 2014, along with Manchester City, which owns Abu Dhabi.
PSG was fined <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>60 million (US$82 million) – which was later reduced to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>20 million – and ordered to reduce the Champions League team to 21 players in the 2014-2015 season, instead of 25 players.
UEFA is looking out for teams that can try to circumvent financial regulators by increasing their revenues through companies affiliated with club owners.
Thus, although the Qatari company sponsors PSG, once the funding exceeds the standard market rate, UEFA has the right to prohibit the invoicing of the amount.
A similar measure was taken by UEFA in 2014 after it decided that the amount of funding provided by the Qatar Tourism Authority to the PSG team was too high.
