NHS Prescribes Controversial HIV Drug to 10,000 Patients
As of September, patients will have access to ‘transformative’ treatments to prevent HIV following a decision by the Supreme Court to fund the NHS drug.
The National Health Service (NSH) has announced that a pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) pill taken before sex, which reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86 percent, will be offered through the health service to approximately 10,000 patients over a three-year trial period.
The NSH agreed to fund a trial period after an appeals court upheld a Supreme Court decision last year stating that the NHS had the funds to pay PrEP despite a statement that the drug should be funded by local authorities.
The decision, which was announced on Thursday, accepted the NHS England from the mouth of CEO Simon Stevens as a “significant intervention,” while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described the decision as a “decisive moment.”
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start accepting patients. Other clinics will join in October and will be fully implemented across England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV medicine administered before sex to reduce the risk of HIV disease.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV transmission among vulnerable patients.
The application of PrEP before sex means that there is a sufficient amount of specific drugs in the patient’s body to prevent infection.
These drugs can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
Tested patients include gay or bisexual men, transgender people, and people with HIV-positive partners who are not treated successfully.
The clinics will designate eligible participants who will sign their consent to participate in testing, including men, women, transgender people and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with GP in the UK can also apply to their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential participation in testing.
The program will come to taxpayers at <0xC2><0xA3>10 million and the NHS of England signed a contract this week to distribute drugs after receiving an international public procurement.
The trial period is designed to collect clinical evidence and assess the full potential of PrEP, its targeting, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: “This important intervention should complement and fully leverage the ever-expanding and increasingly successful HIV prevention effort.
It’s another milestone in a more than 30-year effort to stop one of the biggest challenges to human health.”
Deborah Gold, executive director of the NAT (National Aids Trust), said: “We are witnessing a decisive moment in the fight against HIV.
If PrEP is given correctly and patients are at risk, it will offer the possibility of changing the English HIV epidemic.
Starting in September, the NSH will offer patients at high risk of HIV infection a powerful new tool that is individually controlled and not subject to the need to persuade a partner, which will improve the quality of many lives.
We are pleased to accept this statement.'
Ian Green, CEO of Terrence Higgins Trust, said: “The number one priority must be the rapid deployment of tests across the country; we must ensure that it is accessible to every patient.
We now have the PrEP trial drug at our disposal and we are well on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people at risk of contracting HIV.”
Shadow Health Minister Sharon Hodgson said: “The start of the PrEP trial period is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of delays and delays by the government.
Evidence suggests how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and ending transmission of this life-threatening infection.
Subsequent tests will take us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that we start testing as soon as possible across the country to protect people who are exposed to HIV and together to end the spread of HIV in society."
Living on a high foot: mezzanine and smart design turned this small apartment at Earls Court into a spacious home
Joanne Leigh, a former banker with a passion for real estate, exchanged a large house in Knightsbridge for an apartment on the Earls Cour in 2014.
Located on the first floor of Queen Anne’s smart terrace, it is a striking example of a modern design that makes the most of the space available.
“I used to live with my ex-husband in a much larger house in Knightsbridge,” Joanne said.
“I was looking for something at a more reasonable price.
I ran into this apartment in Earls Court and it had the same ceiling height.
I immediately fell in love with him and nodded at him the same day.”
Since then, the apartment of 1000 square meters has undergone a complete renovation.
One-room apartment with a complicated layout - to get into the bedroom, you had to go through the kitchen - Joanne wanted to add storage space and a mezzanine to take advantage of the high ceiling.
"I longed for a high ceiling, large windows, and a lot of light.
Those were my demands,” she said.
To this end, she hired Erfan Azadi from Notting Hill-based design studio Duck & Shed and used the nearly four-metre ceiling to create a home that was not just a project, but also a place to live.
The ceiling did not reach such height that two gaps would creep over each other - the challenge for architects was to create a mezzanine on which one could walk upright.
Erfan had to engage his creative thinking.
"The steel structure is quite complicated," he explained.
“We had to arrange both spaces so that we could walk upright.
It was not only about building a simple platform, but at the same time bending the steel structure so that at the right height above and below the ceiling."
This arrangement allowed Erfan to construct two full-fledged rooms on top of each other - and at the same time add to the drama.
The mezzanine overlooks the beautiful living room of the old copper window frames in the design of Retrouvius.
Mirrored furniture in gold, silver lines and a retro chandelier by Serge Mouille creates a unique style.
The use of mirrors plays an important role in drama, space and lighting.
The short corridor is equipped with mirrors on both sides and looks longer.
The mirror bar in the kitchen looks like a window to the next room.
At the front door there are storage rooms equipped with mirrors for storing cutlery and glasses.
The advantage of the living room, which gives the whole apartment the impression of significantly more space, is the ability to separate it from the kitchen, if it is not used.
Folding kitchens are nothing new.
However, what is unique about this solution is the folding door.
"We had to solve the technical side," Erfan says of the reinforced veneered doors.
"The door is fitted with counterweights so that it can be unloaded very easily."
Thanks to the smart use of space and storage space, Joanne gained another 16 square meters, a second room and a better overall layout of the apartment.
"When it comes down to it, what you're selling is a living space - or a valuation of your property," Erfan said.
“A real estate agent basically calculates the estimated price when entering the apartment based on the living area.”
In this case, it was possible to increase the living area while maintaining quality materials that give the room a luxurious appearance.
“The material is very important because you touch it and create an emotional bond with your home,” Erfan added.
"You won't love the electricity in the walls.
Yes, they are important, but they won’t win your heart.”
As it turned out, quality design and an increase in living space can turn an ordinary apartment into an exceptional work.
And like Joanne, you can choose to stay in the end.
