Many have tried it before and have always failed.
Maybe John F. Kelly can really do it.
If so, it will be the first.
Politico said the new White House chief of staff plans to curb President Trump’s flow of information — including news reports on television — in the hopes of keeping Trump on the line.
Here is a report by Josh Dawsey:
“When the new White House chief of staff, John F. Kelly, met on his first day in office with his staff, he outlined a key problem Trump’s White House intends to fix: the wrong information that gets in the President’s hands.
Kelly told employees that he had to personally approve all information - whether on paper or by word of mouth - because the president could make better decisions based on the right information."
Kelly’s diagnosis actually makes sense, but many of his predecessors broke their teeth at Trump’s control and media coverage.
Trump’s relationship with the media dates back several decades — and now that he’s sitting in the White House, his habit of watching TV news is even stronger.
“If Trump as a candidate was upset by honest reports, it was appropriate to show him that he was being talked about in a positive light by a lot of other media, which was easier to convince,” Sam Nunberg, a former campaign advisor, told Politico in February.
Tara Palmeri of Politico said: “The key to keeping Trump’s tweets in check – according to at least six former campaign organizers – is to ensure that Trump regularly watches the media that praises him.”
Okay, okay.
But the idea that Trump’s tendency to post his opinions on Twitter was ever “under control” is ridiculous.
Perhaps these campaign organizers know something that others don’t know – that Trump’s tweets would be more outrageous if they weren’t checked.
The tweets that Trump has never sent will most likely never be revealed.
If his employees managed to keep him in check at least a few times, then their efforts did not go in vain.
However, no one has yet been able to regularly prevent Trump from raising controversial topics.
Part of this problem lies in the fact that in the White House, which is made up of rival factions, people regularly try to strengthen their agenda by supplanting Trump’s materials — which may or may not be reliable — that support their view of the world.
In May, the Politico portal, which covered the issue from all sides, published a report on the inclination of advisers to submit questionable information to the head of state.
This is an example of such information from the pen of reporter Shane Goldmacher:
“Current and former Trump officials say the president often reacts very angry to negative media reports, especially leaks, and seeks to find their origin.
This situation occurred at the end of February when someone planted a copy of an article from GotNews.com — the website of provocateur Charles C. Johnson — that accused Deputy Chief of Staff Katie Walsh of being the “source of many leaks” from the White House.
Regardless of the fact that Johnson was forever expelled from Twitter for harassment; or that he did not substantiate his claim with any evidence; or that he had already published false accusations in the past and later dropped them.
Trump read the article and started asking questions about Walsh.
Goldmacher added that then Chief of Staff Reince Priebus and White House Secretary Rob Porter “have tried to implement a system to administer and document the information that President Trump will receive.”
Would that work?
Kelly is now, three months later, trying to push through the same strategy.
He may turn out to be a more effective manager than Priebus, but Trump’s impulsiveness doesn’t just disappear, and his aides are still competing for power.
These immutable factors will certainly complicate Kelly's mission.
