Italians toughen up fight against NGO rescue ships with immigrants on board
Italy has announced that it will prevent the arrival of NGO rescue ships arriving off the coast of Italy with migrants from the Mediterranean Sea unless NGOs sign new rules regulating their operations.
"If the NGOs do not sign the new rules of conduct, it will be difficult for us to imagine that they could continue their operations," Interior Minister Marco Minniti said in an interview with Turin daily La Stampa.
Minniti’s warning came a day after Italian authorities confiscated the ship of the German rescue organization Jugend Rettet on suspicion of human trafficking, which greatly facilitates illegal immigration.
The rescue organisation, which operates for the first year, refused to comment on the case on charges brought by Italian prosecutor Ambrogio Cartosios.
“For us, saving lives is and always will be our number one priority, so we are very sorry that we cannot currently operate in rescue zones,” the organization said in a statement on social media.
“We can only comment on all the current allegations after gathering all the information and evaluating the whole situation.”
Italian authorities have been tracking the Jugend Rettet's Iuventa since October.
Her crew is suspected of transporting migrants on board the ship, which were handed over to them directly by human traffickers, repeatedly.
According to the prosecutor’s file, at least one meeting took place only 1.3 miles off the coast of Libya, according to Italian media.
The crew of the ship is suspected of breaking the law and circumventing the Italian Coast Guard, which oversees rescue operations in the area - out of humanitarian enthusiasm, rather than anything else.
The Code of Conduct establishes the presence of an Italian police officer on board ships such as Iuventa to monitor activities.
Only three of the nine NGOs involved in rescue operations have so far agreed to abide by the code: Save The Children, Malta’s MOAS and Spain’s Pro-Activa Open Arms.
The organisation said Thursday that the new rules are not necessary but acceptable, as they do not represent any "substantial change or impediment" to rescue operations.
Doctors Without Borders (MSF), a Nobel Prize-winning organization, has also rejected the new code of conduct.
Minniti, meanwhile, has been told that the sharp decline in migrants landing in Italy in recent weeks as part of rescue operations suggests that efforts to strengthen patrols off the coast of Libya and cooperation with local mayors bear fruit.
“In recent days, we are beginning to see light at the end of the tunnel,” the minister said.
He also revealed plans for further talks this month with the mayors of Libya on the economic development initiative, as well as with representatives of Chad, Niger and Mali on measures to reduce the number of migrants leaving these countries in the hope of achieving Europe.
