Michelle Carter Sentenced for Sending Text Messages Calling for Conrad Roy's Suicide
A Massachusetts woman has been sentenced to two years in prison for inciting her boyfriend to commit suicide through text messages and phone calls.
Twenty-year-old Michelle Carter will serve 15 months of a two-year prison sentence and then spend five years on parole.
Carter was convicted in June for the unintentional murder of Conrad Roy, who took his own life on July 13, 2014.
Roy’s father told the court on Thursday: “The whole family is devastated.
My son was my best friend.”
Carter was left at large until a decision was made.
She was threatened with up to 20 years in prison, but her lawyers argued that she and Roy suffered from a mental illness.
Dressed in red pants and a creamy blouse, Carter stood on the spot with tears in her eyes, her hands clasped, and her eyes pointing to the ground.
"Her conduct killed Conrad Roy," the plaintiff told the judge.
"She ended his life to relieve herself.
She could not accept her own responsibility," she said.
"She showed no remorse."
But Carter’s attorney said it was “unfortunate circumstances that he deeply regrets.”
Judge Lawrence Moniz added that "her age or level of maturity or even mental disorder has no significant impact on her performance."
The plaintiff read a statement from Roy’s mother, Lynn Roy: “There will not be a single day that I will not mourn the loss of my son.
I want him to be proud of me – I take care of his sisters and together we will endure the immense pain that we will carry with us forever.”
Roy's sister, Camdyn Roy, testified that she was being "stalked" by the knowledge that she would never attend her brother's wedding and would never be his children's aunt.
“The loss of a person I’ve been seeing since I was born is a pain that I will carry with me for life,” she said.
The state of Massachusetts does not have a law in force to punish a person who is aiding another person's suicide, thus setting a legal precedent.
Carter was 17 years old when Roy was found in a car seat poisoned with carbon dioxide in 2014.
The case caught the nation’s attention after Carter’s text messages instigated suicide were published.
"For example, hang yourself, jump out of the building, or stab yourself, I don't care," said the text messages that Carter sent just two weeks before his death when Roy was on family vacation.
A few minutes before her suicide, she wrote to him: “You have to do it Conrad” and “Just put the generator on and you’ll be free and happy.”
Judge Moniz said Carter wanted attention through Roy’s death and ordered her to refrain from any press comments.
The case raised many questions.
One of the people who sided with Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted of murdering her British roommate in Italy in 2007 and was acquitted two years ago.
Ms. Knox, 30, wrote in the Los Angeles Times: “Michelle Carter deserves understanding and help, not jail.”
