Provence lavender is threatened by climate change
Lavender has become a symbol of Provence in the region of southeastern France, but now they are threatened by climate change.
Lavender declines as a result of dry climates and harmful insects, which causes dismay on the faces of researchers and farmers looking for solutions.
Eric Chaisse, an expert at the CRIEPPAM Agricultural Research Institute in Provence, said: “The cultivation of lavender in Provence is at risk because in the last few years this plant has been exposed to climate change, which brings with it less rainfall in the spring and autumn.
This affects the life of lavender.
The cicadas and locusts carrying micro-bacteria that thrive in dry climates are also at fault."
There's a lot at stake.
Lavender attracts tourists and the oil that is produced from them is an important component of perfumes and cosmetics.
Eric Chaisse said: “Instead of long and beautiful flowers, smaller, undeveloped and often weak plants grow.
The amount of oil obtained from these lavender is, of course, less."
A possible solution may be more efficient distribution of water and slowing down the evaporation of water from the soil, but also spraying lavender with a protective mixture of clay and water and breeding more species resistant to dry weather.
Murder of journalist highlights growing threats in Mexico
The staff of Riodoce meet regularly every Wednesday to discuss news of the riots taking place in the Sinaloa area, with organized criminals, corrupt officials, and unrelenting drug wars.
But today, under the pressure of recent events, they meet mainly for their own safety.
They learn the importance of changing their habits.
Two well-deserved journalists talk about what would be safer: take your children with you to an office that someone attacked with a grenade in 2009 or leave them at home.
Security experts have written three simple words on the blackboard: adversaries, neutrals, and allies.
They ask journalists to name every word - no evidence is needed, just imagination and preconception.
To choose them from what - drug traffickers, politicians, traders and journalists are suspected of taking money from the government or drug cartels - a catalog of criminals whose task is to cover up criminal acts.
Violence continues and bodies pile up across the country; journalists are constantly growing: according to the Committee to Protect Journalists, there have been at least 25 since President Enrique Pena Nieto came to power in December 2012; 589 journalists are under federal protection after attacks and threats; and seven have been killed in all seven states this year.
Among them is co-founder of the periodical Riodioce, editor and inspiration for colleagues, Javier Valdez Cardenas.
“The biggest mistake is living in Mexico and working as a journalist,” Valdez wrote in one of his many books on violence linked to the drug trade.
His loss is noticeable, although his presence is pervasive - a large photo of Valdez with the inscription "Justice", on which the middle finger points, hangs in the front of the building; two journalists - Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez - over 30 years old, have a T-shirt with a photo of Valdez with a smile on his face, glasses on his nose and nose.
The meeting takes place less than two months after his death; journalists talk about mutual trauma, nightmares, insomnia and paranoia.
Despite the fact that a special federal prosecutor’s office was established in 2010 to deal with the cases of journalists, the Committee for the Protection of Journalists has so far charged two suspects.
Most of the thousands of murders that take place each year are linked to drug trafficking and organized crime, which makes it very rare for journalists to be put on trial.
Journalists from Riodoce insist on reporting on the violence that is taking place in Sinaloa; despite the fact that they are devastated and the territory is currently very treacherous.
Without information about the killers and without a vision of justice, the security meeting is pointless, Ibarra says.
"It's foolish to waste time on such meetings," he adds.
"If we don't get more information, we can't trust anyone."
On the morning of May 15, Valdez left the headquarters of the Riodoces in Culiacan, the capital of Sinaloa.
He managed to get away a few blocks when his red Toyota Corolla was stopped by two men who pulled him out of the car and killed him with 12 rounds, apparently due to the title of the article - which can be translated as the Twelfth River.
The shooters then boarded his car and crashed him not far from the scene.
Valdez died at the age of 50.
He left behind a wife and two grown children.
Rumors seem to be spreading fast in Culiacan.
In Valdez's case, however, there is a suspicious silence.
Since Guzm<0xC3><0xA1>n’s arrest last year and his January extradition to the United States, Sinaloa has become one of the bloodiest battlegrounds in the country as rival factions try to fill an empty space.
Every day, several people are killed in the streets of Sinaloa, and the cemetery is filled with elaborate two-story mausoleums for drug lords, many of which are larger than houses.
Forget for a moment that the word “ truce” means that a drug cartel controls a coastal state with precious ports and important routes through which drugs travel to the United States.
Despite this, as well as the fact that Valdez was intimately acquainted with the risks of his employment, Ismail Bojorquez, 60, co-founder and director of Riodoce, still blames himself for not protecting his friend.
He believes that two mistakes contributed to his death.
The first was the February issue of an interview with Damaso Lopez, the leader of one of the rival drug cartels that waged war with the sons of Joaqu<0xC3><0xAD>n Guzm<0xC3><0xA1>n.
Peace may have angered the sons; the suspected gang members bought all the copies of the newspaper the moment they landed on the counters.
The second mistake was not to force Valdez to leave the country for his own safety after confiscating other newspapers in which the same story was printed.
Valdez has become a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his death is seen as an important milestone in the fight of Mexican criminals against journalists.
He managed to survive for so long, and all his friends and colleagues believed that it would never change.
In the magazine Noroeste, he was practically a veteran when in 2003 he decided to sell his $50 stock and found together with five colleagues Riodoce.
In Sinaloa, “it was impossible to run a newspaper without mentioning the drug trade,” Bojorquez said.
Over time, Riodoce gained a reputation for brave and truthful reporting; newspapers began to prosper.
Journalists like to search for problematic topics and publish texts without censorship - readers were fascinated by reading stories that no one else dared to publish.
Eight years after its founding, Riodoce won the prestigious Maria Moors Cabot Award for her coverage of Latin America.
In the same year, Valdez won the International Press Freedom Award of the Committee to Protect Journalists for his brave reporting on the Mexican drug trade.
Valdez openly admitted that he was afraid.
“I was worried about my life,” he said in the award ceremony.
Drug trafficking in Sinaloa is “a way of life,” Valdez said in October last year in an interview with Rompeviento TV.
“You have to take on the role of a journalist — or play dumb.
I don’t want anyone to ask me, ‘What did you do in the face of death...why didn’t you say what was going on?’”
The employees of Riodoce miss Valdez. The man was known for his jokes and indiscriminate language. He was a good friend who liked to give advice and hugs - a teacher who knew how to survive.
Everyone relied on his daily routine.
He always wore his hat.
He often went to the El Guayabo bar across from the offices and sat at the same table.
Now they ask: was this routine to blame for his death?
His death also raised questions about his own assumptions - how to do his job best and stay alive?
"They don't like it when you mess with their women, their children, their clean shops, their secret landing sites."
"These things were forbidden," Bojorquez said.
As a result, there is a high level of self-censorship and self-preservation.
You have to trust your instincts.
If you feel like something's wrong here, get your hands off me.
The problem is, Riodoce editor Andres Villarreal said, “smell is a sense that can be fooled... and then the Javier thing happened.”
The old rules no longer apply in Sinaloa, as in the states of Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero and other states that are home to a toxic mix of lucrative smuggling routes, weak governments and corrupt politicians.
The landscape is constantly changing.
No mobile phones are allowed in the room where the Riodoc employees meet; a few days ago, spyware was discovered, which governments bought to monitor Mexican journalists and activists.
In front of the building, two policemen find relief in front of a 40-degree heatwave in the shadow of a nearby tree.
They were selected by the state to protect the offices of Riodoce, which are located in a four-story building in the burgher district of Culiacan.
Journalists are joking about whether these police officers are among the 50 percent of law-enforcers who the government says are corrupt.
It has been several months since journalists last ventured into mountainous areas that essentially control drug cartels.
There are three main stories on this week’s agenda.
The first is the murder of the brother of former boxer Julio César Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez in Sinaloa.
They are also sanctioned for suspicious government expenditures that took place in the hometown of the governor of the state.
Recently, there have also been several kidnappings at one of Culiac<0xC3><0xA1>n's most luxurious restaurants, just a block away from the prosecutor's office.
Officially, no one announced the identity of the abducted people or the circumstances of the kidnapping, so journalists were careful when they were about to write about what every inhabitant of the city knew: that the restaurant was a favorite destination for drug dealers and politicians.
One journalist read out from public records that the restaurant was registered under a name associated with a certain politician who is a member of the Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), controlling all levels of the political scene for almost the entire last century.
Several PRI governors have recently been accused of corruption in senior positions.
Villarreal asked reporters to write about earlier incidents in the restaurant, including an incident in which one of Joaqu<0xC3><0xAD>n's sons, "El Chapo" Guzm<0xC3><0xA1>n, escaped an army intervention unit.
A month ago, readers would have read about this in Valdez’s column, which was the best source of information about kidnappings.
"Valdez would certainly solve the case," said Villarreal, 46, nicknamed "El Flaco" for his slender figure.
"Now all the informants have turned their backs on us."
Valdez's office turned into a warehouse of signs and stickers to protest the killing of journalists. Employees certainly did not expect them to become activists on behalf of the press.
Journalist Miriam Ramirez grabbed several signs and went out the next morning to demonstrate in front of the prosecutor's office for another journalist.
Salvador Adame disappeared just three days after Valdez's murder in the western part of Michoac<0xC3><0xA1>n state.
The only body found was a burnt body, according to the authorities, based on DNA analysis, it was Adame.
The activity of journalists is increasing all over the country, many of them organizing protests and snooping on the sidewalks and buildings of the “SOS press”.
Bojorquez is on a visit to Washington, D.C., seeking international support and justice for Valdez’s death.
At a meeting with Governor Sinaloa the day after Valdez's murder, Ramirez accused the authorities of monitoring journalists and their murders for telling the truth.
Meanwhile, she asked to be transferred to another department for fear that her anger might jeopardize her impartiality.
Valdez has repeatedly said that Mexican journalists are “circumvented” by organized crime, corrupt officials and an indifferent public.
In his latest book, Narco-Journalism, he wrote that journalists die not only at the hands of drug cartels, but also at the request of politicians and security forces who cooperate with organized crime.
Media watchdog Articulo 19 has blamed more than half of all attacks on police and public officials.
"You're going to die in Mexico because they want to silence you," Ramirez said.
The murders obviously work.
No one will forget the death of blogger Marie Elizabeth Mac<0xC3><0xAD>as six years ago at the northern border of Tamaulipas.
Her body was found along with a message allegedly signed by the Zetas cartel: “This is how I ended up because of my messages.”
There was a keyboard and headphones next to the decapitated head.
Some branches have decided to cease operations, such as the newspaper El Norte, based near the northern border of Chihuahua state, in response to the March murder of the reporter Miroslava Breach.
The others continue, as did El Manana of Nuevo Laredo after the assassination of its director in 2004.
In 2010, Diario de Ciudad Juarez publicly addressed drug cartels with an article on the front page entitled “What do you want from us?”
Some journalists fled their homes or even across the border.
It's a difficult decision.
