A Becoming Resemblance: The Artist Creates Portraits Using Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the middle of one of the rooms of the New York Fridman Gallery, there are several faces of different skin shades - white, black and gray - suspended from the ceiling on wires. Each of them seems to fall out of the eye of the previous one.
All 30 portraits were created by the artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from the mouth and hair wipes that Chelsea Manning sent her.
Manning sent her samples from Fort Leavenworth Prison, where a former analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for unauthorized publication of secret cables on WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which began on August 2, is called A Becoming Resemblance.
It is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, who combines her expertise in technology, computer science and the arts, and Manning, a transgender and pioneering dissident whose sentence was commuted by Obama three days before his departure from office.
By algorithmic analysis of Manning's DNA and using 30 portraits to illustrate what a person with this genotype would look like, Dewey-Hagborg created a razor-sharp, if not intellectual, commentary on DNA susceptibility—as well as the many ways DNA can be interpreted—and the inherent determinism of these interpretations, as well as the inherent determinism of these identities.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward Manning, has been talking about considering herself a woman since she was young. She was convicted in 2013 on 20 charges, including violating six espionage laws, computer fraud and theft.
All of her photos were held by prison staff, and only one low-quality black and white photo leaked to the public, on which Manning, visibly concerned, sits in the driver's seat in the platinum-blonde wig she is now associated with.
In 2015, there were still positive reactions to the 2012 Dewey-Hagborg project Stranger Visions.
As part of this project, Dewey-Hagborg used various forensic objects - such as cigarette butts and chewing gums - to create an image of the possible forms of these people.
And it was at this time that she received an email from Paper Magazine.
“They were doing an interview with Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted to add a portrait to the article,” Dewey-Hagborg explained at the opening of the new exhibition.
However, visits and photography were not allowed, so they asked Chelsea if she would be interested in the DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became friends over the course of two years through correspondence.
They even created a comic book called Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanung, which presented a vision of what would have happened if Chelsea had been pardoned and could have attended the exhibition in person.
Indeed, a few days after the release of the comic, President Obama asked for Manning’s release, a welcome change after several unbearable years in a military prison in Kansas.
Interestingly, the exhibition is taking place at a time when Donald Trump is waging war with people who seek to publish government information and transgender soldiers, while trying to find new ways to incite resentment with his tweets in areas he should support.
In response to a question about this particular timing, Dewey-Hagborg stated that “everything happens for a reason.”
Under the statement of the artist on one of the walls of the gallery, Manning calls with her huge signature (the letter "i" in the surname is pierced by the heart) after the end of "self-acting factionalism based on gender, race, sexuality and culture".
On the opposite side are the sequences of her mitochondrial DNA - centipede letters C, G and A recorded with a pencil.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to the artist’s sophisticated scientific dictionary), Dewey-Hagborg wanted to illustrate how surprisingly similar, at least biologically, we are all.
“I hope that people will learn from this, that our genome does not matter who we are, and that genetic data is subjective and everyone can interpret it in their own way,” said Dewey-Hagborg.
“DNA tells a lot of different stories, this is 30 of them.”
The last example of the exhibition, located in a separate room, is the only page from the graphic novel above.
It depicts Manning emerging from the King Kong of the United States Displinary Barracks with a megaphone in her hand.
"Once they stop you from speaking, they'll win," it says.
"Never let yourself be silenced."
"It's a direct transcript from one of the letters," the Philadelphia artist said.
"When I think about it, I get goose bumps."
Manning has not visited the exhibition in person - as predicted in the comic book - but when she does, she will be greeted in the middle of the room with her masks, her own genomic images, arranged like a crowd of Protestants.
This was also the purpose of the exhibition, including the nearly 160 cm tall statue of Maning, on which her genetic haplogroups are recorded with a pencil.
"In the past, they were placed on the walls, but this time I wanted them to radiate the feeling of the crowd," Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
“I wanted to give the impression of a mass movement that takes the form of Chelsea and liberates her.”
