Startups that will help your company not become the next Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure the employee satisfaction of her e-commerce startup, but did not find a suitable survey.
The answers were often inaccurate, useless, or even deceptive.
And despite promising the anonymity of the survey, some employees expressed their distrust in the entire process.
“I was looking for consistency and objectivity,” said Errett, owner of the San Francisco-based e-commerce hair care company Madison Reed, which employs 75 people.
She asked for help from the outside.
New HR startups are constantly appearing on the market to help companies with employee satisfaction surveys.
By creating and licensing software with a specific intent to measure employee responsibilities, startups allow companies to vote quickly, target specific teams and demographics, offer complete employee anonymity and a hotline for complaints, and in some cases also allow whistleblowers to bypass supervisors and contact directors directly.
“There are tools on the market like Strava and Fitbit that monitor your health, but where is Fitbit for your company?” said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of startup Glint based in Reedwood City.
Errett said she gained more awareness in three years of what her employees think and feel.
In addition to quick surveys and vote-specific teams, Glint offers a temperature map of the company and an up-to-date overview of the groups with the highest number of complaints, as well as an overview of low-rated managers - allowing the user to work on the remedy.
Companies are beginning to realize that it is necessary to pay attention to the culture of the work environment - in case they become another Uber - which is being thrown into scandals after a former employee posted on his blog a post describing the corporate environment and harassment of employees who dare to speak out.
For startups like Glint, the demand for corporate culture research is a lucrative business opportunity.
According to the Let’s Talk Payments website, which deals with technical and financial progress, the value of the global control, regulation and compliance industry could exceed $118.8 billion by 2020.
The Denver-based startup Convertent in Colorado, which helps companies prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, saw a slight increase in interest and activity at the start of the year, just ahead of Uber’s scandals.
Convercent’s nearly 600 clients include Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently, Uber has also taken over its wing.
Similar to Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customizable “flash” surveys, collect confidential information in real time, and display temperature maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous text hotline that allows employees to report inappropriate behavior.
If the Director-General is involved in the problem, complaints are sent directly to the Management Board.
“The court of public opinion has authorized regulators,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of Convercent.
If a company is convicted of mistreatment of its employees or unethical behavior – and regulators fail to act – it may face costly consequences as a result of customer boycotts, employee exhaustion or legal proceedings, Quinlan added.
The Ruby Tuesday restaurant network, which employs more than 25,000 people across 500 locations, has been using Convercent for more than a year to raise employees’ awareness of corporate policies and procedures and provide an easy way to contact corporate executives.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report any problem, he had to track down a phone number or e-mail to the company's management, officially file a complaint and hope for a successful solution.
It was often a deterrent and embarrassing experience, said James Vitrano, the general representative of Ruby Tuesday, according to whom there had previously been no reliable way to monitor employee complaints.
Now that the company is using Convercent, it is ensuring rapid detection and resolution of problems that have never before reached managers sitting in offices, miles away from the real solution of complaints - such as discrimination, harassment or unfair treatment.
“It’s getting closer to a holistic, overall view of employee experience,” said Vitrano, who heads the Ruby Tuesday risk management group.
"At the same time, we protect shareholders from litigation by employees."
Companies stopped taking ethics, values, and employee involvement lightly in 2002 after accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed after Enron’s collapse over employee ethical rights abuses, Quinlan said.
But it wasn’t until “social media lit up the whole thing,” that companies began to realize that in the online world, they couldn’t simply hide their skeletons in a closet.
“Before people started using technology to monitor ethics, they relied on faith,” Quinlan said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software in the form of a service for which companies pay regular fees.
It is a business model and an opportunity approved by bold capital investors who have supported both startups.
As part of his February campaign, Convercent raised a total of $10 million from companies such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, and eventually took away $47 million in capital.
Glint raised $10 million from Bessemer Venture Partners in November and earned $60 million throughout the campaign.
