Facebook Plans to Check Facts to Reduce Fake News
Facebook will send more potentially fake articles to third parties to check and display findings under its original posts in an effort to fight so-called “fake news,” the largest social network said on Thursday.
The company says in a statement on its website that it will start using updated machine learning to detect possible hoaxes, which it will send to third parties for verification and potentially display the survey results below the original posts.
Facebook has been identified as one of the main sources of fake news, and many believe that these unconfirmed reports influenced last year’s election of the President of the United States.
French voters are flooded with avalanches of fake news about the May presidential election, and Germany plans to impose a fine on the social media network ahead of the September elections if it does not quickly remove angry posts.
Facebook said in a statement Thursday that it is preparing to launch testing of a new fake news check feature in the US, France, the Netherlands and Germany.
“In addition to displaying third-party authenticated messages, people are asking for more content to be better informed and able to make the right decisions about what they can share,” said Sara Su, Facebook’s product news manager.
