Creating a graphic novel: the story of A Castle in England
The little castle of Scotney Castle recently played a major role in the Squeeze music video, and Margaret Thatcher took refuge in it during the 1970s and 1980s.
However, Scotney witnessed 700 years of turbulent history from his cosy little town on the Bewl River in Kent, UK, which inspired curly-haired Jamie Rhodes of York County – known for his fondness for historical documents – to create a graphic novel.
“The look at the writing of a man who is 300 years after his death fascinates me,” Rhodes says with a serious face.
"When I hold a letter in my hand, I feel a personal connection."
The graphic novel A Castle in England documents the lives of families who lived in Scotney Castle from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian period. Each story is illustrated by a different British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
But this is not Rhodes’ first book inspired by the archives: he is also the author of Dead Men’s Teeth and Other Stories (2014), a collection of British Library-inspired documents – a project that was very emotional for him.
"I was intrigued by the thumbprint on a letter written by a double agent in the '70s who worked for the Jacobites," he said.
"That's his thumbprint!
And letters always smell like smoke, because in those days you had to light a candle to read.
When I smell the letter now, 300 years later, it's like I'm back in time.
I love the archives!”
For someone who is so fascinated by old papers, the support of the National Trust and Arts Council England and the opportunity to stay for almost four months in the castle is almost like a dream.
Rhodes spent his time exploring the Victorian "new" castle, exploring archives, and studying many treasures and curiosities, such as the head of a hyena on a wall and bottles that had been thrown into a ditch for centuries.
He walked around the plot and explored the ruins of the old castle, talking to hay people, gardeners and sometimes artists who worked on illustrations for his book.
At night, he drank whiskey and wrote.
The confidential history of Scotney is relatively unknown, as the National Trust gained access to the documents only in 2006 after the death of the last heir, Elizabeth Hussey.
When Rhodes arrived at the site ten years later, the employees were only beginning to penetrate the archives, which Rhodes described as “the aristocrats of many centuries throwing their hands at the words: ‘Put it in the attic.’”
Diaries, letters from the time of the British Empire, maps showing property: “You might think the land dispute is boring,” Rhodes said, “but I came across one case where two families were dragging on birch.
“Stop it, people!”
Some stories in the book use the castle as a springboard and delve deeper into English history, including a story called The Labourer, which follows a man who leaves a newly built castle to join the English Uprising of 1381.
“I found a record of a rebellion in a castle in 1380, which was called Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex in the book,” Rhodes said.
“The English uprising actually started in this area, and I thought the rebellion was a good starting point.
Maybe they’re somehow related.”
Other stories are closely related to the history of the castle - for example, The Priest, which tells the story of a Jesuit priest who was hidden by the Darrell family for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler about an 18th-century smuggler named Arthur Darrell, who allegedly staged his own funeral when he filled the coffin with stones (which was only discovered a few years after the coffin was discovered).
Rhodes’s favorite family is Darrell’s: “I was intrigued by the male generation – the men at the time were always in debt and were spending money on things they couldn’t afford.
Different generations of the Darrell family dealt with it by marrying rich or old ladies - I imagine they were handsome gentlemen who liked to shake the heads of the heiress."
With the end of his stay at the castle, Rhodes searches for more adventures.
He recently returned from a two-week barn in the Finnish wilderness, where he drew inspiration for his next book about Elämänmäki, a former sanatorium from the early 20th century that was engulfed in nature.
This is a special place for Scotty.
"I was sad when I left," he said.
"I thought, 'Now I'm going to go back to real life.'"
