Red meat, dairy products and chocolate can alleviate symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)
For your digestive system, red meat and dairy products can be a nightmare.
However, a new study suggests the opposite: a diet rich in animal protein and dairy products could help relieve the symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable disease, which affects up to 1.3 million Americans and 300,000 patients in the UK, causes abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Patients are usually reminded not to eat meat and dairy products to relieve symptoms, but researchers at the University of Washington have found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in the protein helps create immune cells that support intestinal resistance.
Study leader Dr. Marco Colonna explained that immune cells protect the intestines and ensure the breakdown of harmful microbes from food.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissue.
Once the scales tilt to the side of the inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease can occur.
As part of the research, the researchers found the presence of immune cells that support tolerance of the body in the stomach of mice with a specific bacterium.
This bacterium requires the presence of tryptophan, one of the building blocks of proteins, to form cells.
Professor Colonna said: “We found a link between one species of bacteria – Lactobacillus reuteri – which is a common part of the intestinal microbiome and the development of cells that support body tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more they had these immune cells.”
At the same time, he suggested that if the same thing turned out to be true for humans, then a combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet would help develop a more tolerable and less inflammatory intestinal environment.
Postgraduate researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas, in a study of a certain type of immune cells supporting body tolerance, found that one group of test mice had these cells, while the other group of the same mice bred separately lacked the cells.
It was derived from the fact that one group of mice has a different intestinal microbiome - a community of bacteria, viruses and fungi that usually reside in the gastrointestinal tract.
The guts of mice were tested by DNA sorting, and the researchers found six types of bacteria in mice with immune cells that were missing from the second group of mice.
Mice that were bred in a sterile environment and lacked a gut microbiome — so they didn’t develop this type of immune cell — were given L. reuteri bacteria — and formed immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers cultivated L. reuteri in the liquid and then transferred a small amount of the liquid - without the bacteria - to the undeveloped immune cells that were kept in isolation.
Immune cells have evolved into tolerant cells.
After removal of the active ingredient from the liquid, it turned out to be a byproduct of tryptophan metabolism known as indolyl-3-acetic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the diet of mice, the amount of these cells increased by 50 percent. After dividing the doses of tryptophan at the same time, the number of cells decreased by half.
Dr Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerant cells as mice, and most of us store L. reuteri bacteria in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether the by-products of tryptophan from L. reuteri cause cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but defects in tryptophan-related genes have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
Dr Cervantes-Barragan added: “Each of us should probably strive to develop these cells because they control the inflammation of the inner surface of the intestines.
Potentially high levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri may increase cell population."
