White House Props Cost Taxpayers Thousands of Dollars
The White House’s decision to fly a Navy helicopter to South Lawn to celebrate the U.S. manufacturing industry last month came at $24,000, according to Navy records published by TIME Weekly.
The green-white Sikorsky VH-3D helicopter, also called Marine One in the presence of the president on board, was the highlight of the July 17 White House program, which was a parade of U.S. design programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and several senior White House officials watched a product show from all 50 states.
A Connecticut helicopter was displayed next to a Maine yacht, a Wisconsin fire truck, and a Mississippi forklift.
A White House military officer issued a fragmentary order, or FRAGO, and requested the helicopter's presence less than 36 hours before the helicopter landed on South Lawn as part of an "extraordinary" event, Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1) records said.
“I wanted to make sure you were aware of such a significant event,” the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his superior, the deputy commander of the Air Force the day before the event began.
The report indicated that the helicopter would arrive at South Lawn on July 17 at approximately 7:00 a.m. on the occasion of the parade, which is scheduled to begin at 3 p.m. and remain in place until the complete clearing of the entire site, which was scheduled between 6 p.m. and 9 p.m.
The email also stated that if there is a delay in the departure of the flight from the White House, a replacement crew will be sent for the return flight due to the regulations on working hours.
The original crew remained on the scene that evening, along with the helicopter and a unit of security personnel.
From the records - obtained by TIME - it was not clear whether the second crew had been sent in the end.
The Hatch Act prevents government officials from using government property for political purposes.
The records indicate that HMX-1 is investigating possible violations of this regulation.
"We were wondering if it was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were assured that everything was fine," the commander wrote.
'It sounds like you've been blocked, 'said the deputy commander.
This "Made in America" show was designated by the White House as an official event, and the Hatch Act would therefore not apply to it.
But even official events have political subtexts.
During his participation in the event, the president promoted health reform, which passed through the Senate, and spoke about trying to keep government regulations in check.
The use of aircraft such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents use them when traveling.
However, their presence purely for presentation reasons is unusual.
Trump ordered a check in February after a presidential plane was flying in the background at his first rally as part of a campaign in Melbourne, Florida. His Twitter account is swamped with complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessors.
“The White House is delighted with the ‘Made in America’ show, which showcases products from all 50 states made by Americans from American materials,” said Lindsay Walters, a spokeswoman for the White House.
The crews of the HMX-1 helicopter often train landings in the Washington and South Lawn areas, and train any arrivals with the President of the United States to the White House with maximum accuracy.
While Trump attended the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 training landings at the White House.
The flight to the Made in America parade was part of the crew’s current training, a state official said.
On the same day, a helicopter unit flew another 11 hours as part of a “non-presidential support mission.”
The White House said no additional requisites had been paid from taxpayers' money.
A spokesman for Sikorsky said the company was not in any way involved in the negotiations to expose the helicopter to the South Lawn.
The HMX-1 does not keep records of the budget for presidential flights, and the exact costs associated with the parade are difficult to determine, according to the Navy.
According to the Department of Defense, the hourly price for fiscal year 2017 is $24,380 per flight hour for DoD expenses for VH-3D.
The unit's records show a time of 30 minutes from Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico in Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the actual operating costs of the helicopter are well below that amount.
“It’s very misleading to state taxpayer costs based on estimates for reimbursement,” Walters said.
“These estimates include personnel, maintenance and many other hidden costs that are included in the annual cost.”
According to the 2015 RAND study, the reimbursements of DoD expenditure do not include personnel costs, but include fuel price, maintenance and contract costs.
The White House press secretary at the time, Sean Spicer, defended the use of the helicopter for the purpose of the parade.
“The idea behind the show this week is to introduce products made in the U.S.,” Spicer said.
“I am aware that Sikorsky and the State of Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they are contributing to the defense of our state and that they are providing jobs to hundreds, if not thousands, of people.
I think, like most Americans, that we are proud of the helicopter and other military equipment that countless American citizens are involved in.
This fact is worth remembering.”
It is not clear whether Trump during his tour of South Lawn was also looking at the helicopter. It can only be said with certainty that he sat behind the wheel of one of the fire trucks.
Back at the White House, Trump approached Sikorsky and joked with the media about his own product fleet.
"I know Sikorsky very well," said the President, "I own three of them."
